CONTEXT

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

OBJECTIVE

Customers’ leaving credit card services would lead the bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and the reason for same – so that the bank could improve upon those areas. We need to explore the data provided, identify patterns, and come up with a classification model to identify customers likely to churn, and provide actionable insights and recommendations that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards.

Model Building - Original Data¶

Let us consider what is the effect of false positives and false negatives on the problem statement that can help determine the evaluation metrics to optimise.

False positive - Predicting that a customer will attrite when they actually won't will lead to a loss of processing resources False negative - Predicting that a customer will not attrite when they actually will, will lead to loss of business

False negatives will have a more negative impact for the bank and hence the model needs to drive towards reducing false negatives. Hence, recall of the model is the best evaluation metric.

Preparing some common functions that can be used to evaluate models henceforth:

In [374]:
#Building common functions to display model performance
def confusion_matrix_map(model, target, predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, predicted)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, cmap="flare", fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("Truth")
    plt.xlabel("Prediction")
    
def model_performance(model, target, predicted):
    print('Confusion Matrix:')
    print(confusion_matrix_map(model, target, predicted))
    print('Classification Report:')
    print(classification_report(target, predicted))

def get_metrics(model, X_a, X_b, y_a, y_b):
    # use model to predict on both X_a and X_b
    score_list = []
    y_pred_a = model.predict(X_a)
    y_pred_b = model.predict(X_b)
    train_f1_score = f1_score(y_a, y_pred_a)
    test_f1_score = f1_score(y_b, y_pred_b)
    train_acc_score = accuracy_score(y_a, y_pred_a)
    test_acc_score = accuracy_score(y_b, y_pred_b)
    train_recall_score = recall_score(y_a, y_pred_a)
    test_recall_score = recall_score(y_b, y_pred_b)
    train_precision_score = precision_score(y_a, y_pred_a)
    test_precision_score = precision_score(y_b, y_pred_b)
    
    print("Accuracy on training data: ", train_acc_score)
    print("Accuracy on test data: ", test_acc_score)
    print("Recall score on training data: ", train_recall_score)
    print("Recall score on test data: ", test_recall_score)
    print("Precision score on training data: ", train_precision_score)
    print("Precision score on test data: ", test_precision_score)  
    print("F1 score on training data: ", train_f1_score)
    print("F1 score on test data: ", test_f1_score)
    score_list.extend((train_acc_score, test_acc_score, train_recall_score, test_recall_score, 
                       train_precision_score, test_precision_score, train_f1_score, test_f1_score))
    #return the score list for final comparison
    return score_list

def evaluate_models(models, xtrain, ytrain, seed):
    # comparison dataframe
    comp_metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Train Folds Acc', 'Test Fold Acc', 'Train Folds Recall', 
                                            'Test Fold Recall', 'Train Folds Precision', 'Test Fold Precision', 'Train Folds f1', 'Test Fold f1'])
    #evaluation metrics for comparing model scores
    scoring_params = ('recall', 'precision', 'accuracy', 'f1')
    
    #setup the 10-fold strategy on training data
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)
    
    #loop through the models
    for idx, model_tuple in enumerate(models):
        # to avoid data leakage set scaler inside the pipeline so that for every iteration of train and test fold, the folds are scaled
        pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('scaler', RobustScaler()), model_tuple])
        # pipe represents the model, so calculate cross validation recall, precision, accuracy, f1 scores
        scores = cross_validate(estimator=pipe, X=xtrain, y=ytrain, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring_params, return_train_score=True)
        # take all scores per model to populate in a dataframe for comparison
        # Train fold scores is the average of all scores that have run for each iteration on k-1 = 9 folds
        # Test fold scores is the average of all scores that have run for each iteration on test fold
        comp_metrics_df.loc[len(comp_metrics_df.index)] = [model_tuple[0], np.mean(scores['train_accuracy']), np.mean(scores['test_accuracy']), 
                                                           np.mean(scores['train_recall']), np.mean(scores['test_recall']), 
                                                           np.mean(scores['train_precision']), 
                                                           np.mean(scores['test_precision']), np.mean(scores['train_f1']), 
                                                           np.mean(scores['test_f1'])]
    return comp_metrics_df

In [398]:
# defining model pipeline; scaler included
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('scaler', RobustScaler()), ('Tuned UpSampled GradientBoost', GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=seed))])

# Parameter grid to pass in RandomizedSearchCV
param_grid={'Tuned UpSampled GradientBoost__n_estimators':np.arange(100, 1000, 100),
            'Tuned UpSampled GradientBoost__learning_rate':np.arange(0.05, 1, 0.05)} 

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

#Calling RandomizedSearchCV
gradient_up_tuned = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=pipe, param_distributions=param_grid, n_iter=20, scoring=scorer, cv=10, 
                                       random_state=seed, n_jobs = -1)

#Fitting parameters in RandomizedSearchCV
gradient_up_tuned.fit(up_X_train,up_y_train)

print("Best parameters are {} with CV score={}:" .format(gradient_up_tuned.best_params_,gradient_up_tuned.best_score_))

Model Performance Comparison and Final Model Selection¶

From the above analysis, we find that Tuned GradientBoost model on the downsampled data seems to be the best fit model with a recall score of 94% for both 'attrited' and existing customers. It also enjoys an accuracy score of 94%. The model generalises well over test data and hence does not overfit.

Insights¶

  • The features that are most critical* to the model are Total_Trans_Ct, Total_Trans_Amt, Total_Revolving_Bal, Total_Relationship_Count, Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1, Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1*
  • *All the key features that influence the model have a negative correlation with attrition flag. The lower the values of these features for a customer, the higher the chance of attrition*
  • The attrition of customers does not depend much on demographics, education, income category and card category. It is mostly dependent on the quality of relationship* with the bank*

Recommendations¶

  • Bank should focus on schemes and offers on the credit cards* that make them use the card more often. Cashbacks, reward or loyalty points, privileged access etc., can help customrs engage more with the credit cards.*
  • Bank should look into customisable products* so that it can increase the relationship count. This an help customer spend categorisation and they may use different cards based on benefits*
  • Bank should periodically revise the credit limit* so that customer can purchase big ticket items*
  • Bank should look into easy debt repayment options, provide longer time for due date etc.,**
  • Bank can look into offerings that increases the volume of small purchases* or provide more rewards on big purchases. Depending on the customer, both can increase the relationship quality*
  • Bank should cross sell internal product tieups with credit card* to maintain healthy relationship count*
